        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2017-08-25 13:28:55.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nProbably even better if we can just use \"apt-get install redis-server\".  Not sure they have specific requirements for the version of redis they wanted to download.",
        "patchset_number": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "b653b6f63870ee30c587904339766e170529cbcd",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 481,
          "name": "Jessica Wagantall",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jwagantall@linuxfoundation.org",
          "username": "jwagantall"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2017-08-25 18:04:03.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nThanks Gary, \nActually, they don't need a specific version for this, just as long as we can run \"redis-server\" is fine (also, no extra specific configuration is needed for these tests). I tried your apt-get install redis-server command locally which would work, but shouldn't line 11 be taking care of that already?\n\nAnother thing we can do is adding \"redis-server &\" as part of the job builder step just for the particular jobs that need it.",
        "patchset_number": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "e82fcfdcad70e9051e71db0de5ec75712026ceaf",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 35,
          "name": "Gary Wu",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "gary.wu@gmail.com",
          "username": "gwu"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2017-08-25 18:30:16.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nLine 11 \"yum install\"?  That is only run for CentOS which wouldn't apply in this case.  If the apt-get version works, then we should replace the entire contents of the ubuntu_systems() function with \"apt-get -y install redis-server\".  I think the apt-get installation would setup redis-server to start on boot.",
        "patchset_number": 2
      },
